comments: Never thought I'd enjoy a romance but what a movie

This film misses the point about Bipolar disorder and depression in general.
Wishful thinking doesnâ€™t cure depression. And therapy by itself doesnâ€™t cure a chemical imbalance in the brain that causes deep depression. Saying stay positive is a nonsensical answer to depression.

You have a shot at a Silver lining if you stay positive is also a useless statement. I suffered from deep depression years ago. If someone said stay positive to me that meant nothing. I felt like I was in a dark hole mentally that I couldnâ€™t climb out of by myself. And I was suicidal. I somehow got through those dark days and the dark thoughts in my head lifted. Now I realize I was in danger and needed professional help. So this movie is not going to help anyone with Bipolar disorder or depression.

And Bipolar disorder is very real.
I knew someone at work who had it and without his meds his behavior was very unstable and unpredictable. I never knew what he was going to say or do. He was potentially dangerous. Luckily he quit.

I don't understand why it's so incredibly hard for Hollywood to ACTUALLY make biopics about the discoveries, hardships, and struggles these scientists, engineers, doctors and businessmen faced when dealing with some sort of underlying scientific foundation. These scripts do not need to be spoon-fed or dumbed down for audiences, It needs to stick with a centralized and focused point about the person in question. This for example could've talked greatly about how Hawking came about with his theories regarding black holes and delve into such topics as Hawking Radiation, Black Hole Entropy, The Singularity or even the Information Loss Paradox which by the could tie nicely in with Hawking's feud with another famous physicist Leonard Susskind. But no, they've decided to make another "Hollywood" story that focuses more on Hawking's relationship with his wife Jane and how they both cope with his ALS probably for the sake of another emotional baggage love story.Â 

Primer is a great example of what I'm talking Â about. AND Shane Carruth, director and actor in the movie, actually has a background in software engineering and mathematics, so the way he presents his story is reflected through his script's technical dialogue which added a layer of depth to his story, which I personally loved.

If this is how keeps going with Jobs and now this, I'm just keen on the day they decide to make a biopic about Newton, Einstein, Darwin, Tesla, Bohr, Planck, Fleming, or even the great David Hilbert and have it NOT have to do ANYTHING with their personal struggle to find exactly what they wanted from their lifetime and what they wanted to achieve, and instead focus some other innocuous aspect about their life which deters so much away from what they actually accomplished that it almost gives the audience an entirely wrong perspective of the person they truly are and/or what the difficulties and struggles they went through to become some of the most well respected, most influential people in human history.

Fuck you Hollywood. I'm done.Â 

Note: Despite all that I have said, this does look like a fairly well crafted movie, and I will probably go see it with my friends when it comes out.

comments: Wow. Looks amazing
RESPECT!

I have a personal theory that the thing most responsible for Dr. Hawking being alive today,more than anything else in his post diagnosis world, save for the exception of his wife, is that little computer. Not in any measurable way. It doesn't regulate any body part I'm aware of, except one. His mind! By giving him the ability to allow his ideas to escape.

Ask any creator or artist and they will tell you that the most distressing part of creating, is not being able to express the ideas that take hold of your mind and demand to be released into the world. The all consuming compulsion to have life charged into your thoughts by making them tangible in some way. Trust me Theoretical Physics and Mathematics take just as much creativity and abstract thinking as any song or painting. Look at the concept Einstein's theory of Special Relativity (E=MCÂ²) presents, with such beauty and elegance, then tell me honestly you don't see art in it.

If Dr. Hawking was to be, not only bed ridden, immobilized, but silenced by his disease as well, I would imagine his life would have ended much earlier. Instead of the 100 years from now, where he will pass away as the result of being shot by the jealous husband of a 22 year old centerfold model. Like Dr. Hawking can help how sexy women find his big... brain!

Seriously though. I don't mean just his ability to describe a problem to those who assist him with his health. That may obviously be the difference in life and death, but that of his personal worth, gained from the mono-tone American accent of his computer.

I imagine this man is so full of thought and reasoning that his mind is even defying death itself. It is like his physical life is more horrifying than an H.R.Giger painting but still, he treks on. Not only because of his love for his wonderful and saintly wife but because he has purpose and with purpose comes drive. With drive you gain resolve and with resolve, life. He is here not just for himself and his loved ones but for us. Believing that this world is the only chance you get at existence. That with that belief, the closest you get to immortality is being remembered by the world for you deeds. I think his memory will always be that of a teacher. Just think of all the profound ways in which he teaches us. Not just in his field of study but in his life. All while never saying a word with his own breath. I admire, respect, and adore Hawking on each and every level we usually judge one another.

comments:
Wesley Gibson (James McAvoy) is an office worker whose life is going nowhere. After his estranged father is murdered, he meets Fox (Angelina Jolie), who recruits him into the Fraternity, a secret society of assassins which takes its orders from Fate itself. Fox and Sloan (Morgan Freeman), the Fraternity's leader, teach Wesley to tap into dormant powers. Though he enjoys his newfound abilities, he begins to suspect that there is more to the Fraternity than meets the eye.


James McAvoy as Wesley Gibson, a meek 24-year-old who works in a cubicle, but learns he is heir to a career as an assassin.
Morgan Freeman as Sloan, leader of the Fraternity and partner of Wesley's deceased father.
Angelina Jolie as Fox, an accomplished member of the Fraternity who mentors Wesley.
Thomas Kretschmann as Cross, a rogue assassin who has left the Fraternity, and later revealed to be Wesley's real father.
Common as Earl Spellman a.k.a. "Gunsmith", a professional gunman who trains others to use weapons.
Konstantin Khabensky as "The Exterminator", an expert in explosives who makes bombs and attaches them to rats. One of Wesley's only friends in the Fraternity.
Marc Warren as "The Repairman", an assassin who says he "breaks bad habits" by violently beating people. Trains Wesley in hand-to-hand combat and endurance.
Dato Bakhtadze as "The Butcher", a knife-expert. Trains Wesley in knife fighting.
Terence Stamp as Pekwarsky, a master in the science of killing. Pekwarsky operates as a rogue agent outside of The Fraternity. He is also a craftsman who is able to build bullets both untraceable and capable of traversing long distances. One of Cross's compatriots.
David O'Hara as Mr. X, the first Fraternity member. Said to be the greatest assassin, and believed to be Wesley's father. His murder is the catalyst for Wesley's introduction into the Fraternity. He is killed by Cross.
Chris Pratt as Barry, Wesley's co-worker and best friend, who is having an affair with Wesley's girlfriend.
Kristen Hager as Cathy, Wesley's unfaithful and bickering girlfriend.
Sophiya Haque as Puja
Lorna Scott as Janice, Wesley's overbearing boss.
